# infrastructure/containers

Local Docker Compose setup for the `{{ lg_agent_dir }}` FastAPI chat-agent service (`{{ py_project_root }}/{{ ai_source_root }}/agents/{{ lg_agent_dir }}`).

## Quickstart

```sh
make setup            # uv sync, creates .env from .env.example
make corpus-ingest     # builds data/stores/vectordb.duckdb on the HOST (see below)
make docker-up         # docker compose up --build
make docker-down       # stop and remove the containers
```

`docker-up` / `docker-down` are Makefile targets that run:

```sh
docker compose -f infrastructure/containers/docker-compose.yml up --build
docker compose -f infrastructure/containers/docker-compose.yml down
```

## Why corpus ingestion happens on the host, not in the container

`data/` is bind-mounted into the container (`../../data:/app/data`) rather than baked
into the image, so the DuckDB index you build persists across container rebuilds and
is easy to inspect/rebuild from the host. That means **you must run
`make corpus-ingest` on the host before `make docker-up`** — the container does not
run ingestion itself, and `{{ lg_agent_dir }}`'s `/chat` endpoint will error against an empty
index (see the warning `main.py` prints on startup if `VECTORDB_PATH` doesn't exist).

This is a reasonable starter pattern for local dev, but not how you'd want to deploy
for real: a real deployment would either bake a pre-built index into the image at
build time (fine for a small, infrequently-changing corpus) or run ingestion as a
one-off init container / job against a shared volume or object store before the
service starts (better for a corpus that changes independently of the app image).

## Configuration

The container reads its environment from the project root `.env` (via
`env_file: ../../.env` in `docker-compose.yml`) — the same file `make {{ lg_agent_dir | replace('_', '-') }}-up` uses
outside Docker. See `.env.example` for the full list of variables
(`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, `LG_MODEL`, `LG_PORT`, `VECTORDB_PATH`, `LG_CHECKPOINTER`).

**Known limitation — changing `LG_PORT`:** the container's *listening* port always
follows `LG_PORT` from your root `.env` correctly (via `env_file`). However, the
*host-side* port mapping in `docker-compose.yml` (`"${LG_PORT:-8010}:${LG_PORT:-8010}"`)
is resolved by Docker Compose's own variable interpolation, which only looks at the
invoking shell's environment or a `.env` file sitting next to `docker-compose.yml`
itself — it does not read the root `.env`. If you change `LG_PORT` away from the
default `8010`, either:

- `export LG_PORT=9001 && make docker-up`, or
- drop a `infrastructure/containers/.env` with just `LG_PORT=9001` in it.

Otherwise the host mapping silently stays on `8010` while the container listens on
whatever port you set — a mismatch that will make the service unreachable at the
old port. This is a known Compose quirk (`env_file` vs. compose-file interpolation
are separate mechanisms), not a bug in this template; a real deployment would
likely fix the port with a build/deploy-time value instead of runtime env.

## Files

- `docker-compose.yml` — single `{{ lg_agent_dir }}` service: builds from the project root
  (needs `src/`, `core/`, `pyproject.toml`, `uv.lock`), mounts `../../data`, exposes
  `LG_PORT`, and healthchecks `GET /health`.
- `{{ lg_agent_dir }}/Dockerfile` — `python:{{ python_version }}-slim` + `uv sync --no-dev --frozen`, then
  runs `uvicorn agents.{{ lg_agent_dir }}.main:app` directly (no `.env` is ever copied into
  the image — secrets only ever arrive via `docker-compose.yml`'s `env_file`).
